h in the Business and Management Field</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-451-25-4218</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This seminar series is organised by members of the British Academy of Management Special Interest Group in Research Methodology. The series aims to bring together a range of both experienced and junior management researchers; practitioners; and consumers of management research to discuss key questions that impact upon the future of research in the business and management field. As such it provides a unique opportunity to take an innovative approach to examining the significant issues that currently challenge those within the management research area.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>The specific questions we will be addressing are:&lt;br />&lt;/p> 
&lt;ul> 
 &lt;li>How can we enhance capacity and capability in the field of management research? &lt;br />&lt;/li> 
 &lt;li>How can we most effectively develop management researchers? &lt;br />&lt;/li> 
 &lt;li>How can the quality of management research be enhanced? &lt;br />&lt;/li> 
 &lt;li>Who should management research be for, and whom should its outputs be aimed at? &lt;br />&lt;/li> 
 &lt;li>How can management research be made more practitioner-friendly? &lt;br />&lt;/li> 
 &lt;li>How should we be developing theories of managerial practice? &lt;br />&lt;/li> 
 &lt;li>How can management research become more internationally focused? &lt;br />&lt;/li> 
 &lt;li>How can management researchers diversify to use a greater variety of methodological tools and techniques? &lt;br />&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul> 
&lt;p>Our objective therefore is to provide an arena in which these challenges to the future of management research can be meaningfully discussed.&lt;/p> 
